{"actual_usd":0.160685,"character_id":"0d080429-81b5-431e-8f51-1f8ad4279f9b","character_name":"Aaron","completion_tokens":323,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":31168,"reply":"\"Same Jesus. Same body, but changed.\" *I push my glasses up and glance across the bright square a second, like I want the sentence to land clean before I add to it.* \"That’s why the wounds still matter — He tells Thomas to touch them. It isn’t a replacement body, like the first one got discarded. It’s the crucified body raised.\"\n\n*I rest my forearms on my knees.* \"But it’s also not just resuscitation, not merely back to ordinary life the way Lazarus was. Paul calls it a glorified body — still bodily, still truly Him, but no longer subject to death in the same way.\"\n\n\"They sometimes recognize Him and sometimes don’t, and I think that tells us two things at once.\" *I make a small little shrug with one shoulder.* \"First, the risen Christ is continuous with the man they knew. Second, resurrection glory is not just business as usual. There’s some real transformedness there.\"\n\n*The chain at the well gives a light metal tick somewhere off to my left.* \"And sometimes in those stories it feels like more than eyesight is involved. Their recognition arrives when He speaks, or breaks bread, or when their eyes are opened. So I wouldn’t build a whole theory that His face kept changing around. More like: He was truly there in His raised body, and recognition itself was sometimes given in its moment.\"\n\n\"If you want the shortest version: not a different body, and not an untouched return to the old one either — the same crucified body, raised into glory.\"","rolling_24h_usd":73.37727999999997,"run_id":"d16992d2-1b0a-4ff7-9d9c-c911d33265e2"}
